#Text=Melbourne/Inner north
#Text=Melbourne 's inner north is a vibrant and diverse area , home to a number of cultural and social icons of Melbourne .
#Text=It is famed for the popular Lygon Street Italian district , while next door lies the University of Melbourne , the best university in Australia by many rankings .
#Text=Numerous backpackers subside in the residential and cosmopolitan area of North Melbourne , just outside the city centre .
#Text=Major tourist attractions such as the Melbourne Museum , Royal Exhibition Building and Melbourne Zoo are in the district .
#Text=Much of the area is covered by parks , including the huge Royal Park in the north , the UNESCO-listed Carlton Gardens and popular Princes Park .
#Text=The area is bounded by Brunswick Road in the north , Victoria Street in the south , Nicholson Street in the east and the CityLink freeway in the west .
#Text=Understand
#Text=Carlton is the largest part of the district , and the traditional home of Melbourne 's many Italian residents , most of whom settled in the city in the wake of the Second World War .
#Text=The area 's epicentre is restaurant-lined Lygon Street .

#Text=Besides dozens of Italian restaurants and pizzerias to choose from , the street is also home to countless cafés , making Carlton somewhat of a pilgrimage destination for Melbourne 's caffeine addicts .
#Text=Interspersed amongst these eateries are theatres , museums and numerous sellers of fresh food produce , which have ensured the street remains one of Melbourne 's most lively places .

#Text=Melbourne Museum occupies a huge post-modern complex in the otherwise tranquil Carlton Gardens , which along with the beautiful Royal Exhibition Building forms one of only two of Australia 's cultural UNESCO World Heritage sites .
#Text=A large part of the inner north forms the city 's University district , housing the world-renowned and prestigious University of Melbourne in Parkville .
#Text=The large student population enjoys the university 's wide variety of architecture , ranging from grand old colleges from the 1800s to ultramodern structures of glass and steel .
#Text=Parkville 's north is covered by the massive expanse that is Royal Park , which offers a peaceful spot for a picnic in an otherwise busy city .
#Text=Melbourne Zoo resides within the park , housing hundreds of species from Australia and around the world in generous enclosures .
#Text=North Melbourne is another cosmopolitan locality , which is still finding its feet as one of Melbourne 's cultural hotspots .
#Text=Mostly a residential area of wide , grassy avenues , it is the site of an old town hall , an upmarket strip of cafés and hidden bars and a variety of budget and backpacker accommodation .
#Text=Get in
#Text=Lying a kilometre or two north of the City Centre , Carlton , North Melbourne and Parkville can be easily reached by road , tram , bus , bike and even on foot .
#Text=By tram
#Text=Carlton is well connected by tram from the City Centre .
#Text=All Swanston St and St Kilda Rd trams travel north to Carlton , with most terminating at the University of Melbourne tram stop , a short walk to Lygon Street .
#Text=Routes 1 and 8 continue along Lygon Street ( albeit a little north of all the action ) to East Brunswick and Coburg in the north .
#Text=Nicholson Street ( for Melbourne Museum ) is served by Route 96 towards East Brunswick from along Spring Street , Bourke Street and Spencer Street in the City Centre .
#Text=Nicholson Street also represents the division between Carlton and Fitzroy .
#Text=For Parkville , Route 19 runs along Royal Parade from Elizabeth Street , continuing to North Coburg .
#Text=Alternatively , Route 55 from along William Street travels past the Parkville Hospital precinct , through Royal Park and passes by Melbourne Zoo .
#Text=The number 19 tram , which runs on Elizabeth Street in the CBD is an easy and scenic way to get to Brunswick .
#Text=The tram passes through Royal Parade on its way to Sydney Road , passing many historic buildings , some of them part of the University of Melbourne .
#Text=The 55 tram , which runs through West Brunswick , is not recommended for tourists to Brunswick ; it mostly passes through boring suburban streets , with the exception of the Royal Zoo .
#Text=By bus

#Text=The busiest part of Lygon Street is served by buses 200 and 207 from Lonsdale and Queen Streets in the City Centre , which operate at a 10 minute frequency between them ; these routes also link the area to Melbourne 's inner east along Johnston Street .
#Text=Rathdowne Street is served by buses 250 and 251 , which can also be caught from Lonsdale and Queen Streets .
#Text=Alternatively , the Melbourne Visitor Shuttle operates via the inner north , stopping at Melbourne University on Grattan St and Lygon St.
#Text=By train
#Text=Carlton is not served by Melbourne 's suburban railway network , while Royal Park station on the Upfield Line is the only station in Parkville , adjacent to Melbourne Zoo .
#Text=By bike
#Text=Due to the high student population , cycling is a very popular mode of transport , which has pressured the government to provide the appropriate infrastructure .
#Text=A segregated cycleway runs along Swanston Street from the City Centre to the University of Melbourne .
#Text=Additionally , many streets have painted bike lanes , including Royal Pde , Queensberry St , Rathdowne St , Arden St , Flemington Rd and Elgin St.
#Text=Although it is legal to ride on any road , Lygon and Grattan Streets are generally unsuited to bikes due to their busy nature .
#Text=Additionally , bike trails are plentiful in Royal Park .
#Text=By car
#Text=Most of the City Centre 's north-south streets extend into Carlton .
#Text=Lygon Street is an extension of Russell Street in the city , Rathdowne Street of Exhibition Street , while Nicholson Street is connected directly to Spring Street .
#Text=In Parkville , Royal Parade is the extension of Elizabeth Street .
#Text=From the airport , the Flemington Rd exit off CityLink is the best way to reach the inner north .
#Text=Get around
#Text=The inner north is generally very walkable , although covers a large distance .
#Text=Trams and buses serve the main north-south thoroughfares , although it can be difficult getting east-west by public transport .

#Text=The Route 402 bus operates at a 10 minute daytime frequency , providing an east-west link between Footscray and East Melbourne , through Macauley Rd in North Melbourne and Grattan St in Parkville and Carlton , past Melbourne University .
#Text=See
#Text=Carlton Gardens , 1-111 Carlton St , Carlton ( A short walk from the city , or tram routes 30 or 35 ( City Circle ) : Stop 9 ) .
#Text=Beautiful European-style gardens featuring a number of towering plane trees and majestic fountains , some of which date from the Victorian era .
#Text=It 's a World Heritage Site along with the Royal Exhibition Building there .
#Text=Grainger Museum , Gate 13 , Royal Pde , University of Melbourne , Parkville ( Tram route 19 : Stop 11 ) , ☏ +61383445270 , ✉ grainger@unimelb.edu.au .
#Text=Su - F
#Text=12-4pm. A small but fascinating autobiographical museum on the university 's fast western side .
#Text=Documents the life and times of Percy Grainger , a Victorian concert pianist who achieved international fame and success .
#Text=In addition to the Grainger collection , there is also a broader variety of items relating to music .
#Text=Free , tours $ 5 .

#Text=Ian Potter Museum of Art ( The Potter ) , 801 Swanston St , University of Melbourne , Carlton ( Any Swanston St tram : Stop 1 ) , ☏ +61383445148 , fax : +61393493518 , ✉ potter-info@unimelb.edu.au .
#Text=Tu - F 10AM-5PM , Sa - Su 12-5PM. Houses and displays the university 's wide collection of artworks , from classical antiquity to the contemporary , of Australia and European origin .
#Text=Temporary exhibitions of other artefacts and artworks are regularly hosted .
#Text=Free .

#Text=Italian Museum ( Museo Italiano ) , 199 Faraday St ( Bus routes 200 or 207 : Faraday St stop ; or short walk from any Swanston St tram : Stop 1 ) , ☏ +61393499000 , ✉ info@museoitaliano.com.au .

#Text=Tu - F 10AM-5PM , Sa 12-5PM. Recounts the history of the tens of thousands of Italian migrants that came to Melbourne following World War II , including the impact that they 've had on Australian culture .
#Text=Also details the story of the Lygon Street precinct and how it has developed over time .
#Text=Includes a number of permanent and rotating exhibitions .
#Text=Royal Park , Parkville ( Royal Park Station or Route 55 tram ) .
#Text=An expansive park just north of the city centre , containing grasslands , native gardens and many sporting facilities .
#Text=It is also home to the city 's zoo .
